      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling in Virginia 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Virginia is a northern Brisbane suburb with a genuine industrial-residential mix, consistent investor demand, and an airport corridor location that attracts a specific buyer profile. Here is what sellers need to know before listing in 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Virginia sits approximately thirteen kilometres north of the Brisbane CBD, positioned between Chermside and the Brisbane Airport precinct in a stretch of the northern corridor that is neither purely residential nor purely industrial. That mixed character defines the suburb's identity and shapes the buyer pool that sellers need to understand. Virginia has not historically attracted the same attention as its residential neighbours Aspley and Chermside, but that relative obscurity sits alongside genuine practical advantages: Airport Link access, proximity to Westfield Chermside, affordable price points, and a consistent investor demand that reflects the suburb's employment catchment. Sellers in 2026 who understand these dynamics are better positioned than those who simply list and wait.</p>

      <p>The suburb's landscape is defined by a combination of residential pockets, Virginia Golf Club, and industrial and commercial precincts along the major roads. The residential quality varies significantly across the suburb, and buyers are aware of these distinctions. Properties in the suburb's quieter residential streets, away from the industrial activity, attract a fundamentally different buyer profile than those with industrial neighbours or main-road exposure. Understanding where your property sits in the suburb's internal hierarchy is the starting point for pricing and presentation decisions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Virginia</h2>
      <p>The investor is the dominant buyer in Virginia. The suburb's combination of accessible price points, solid rental demand from the northern employment corridor and airport precinct, and proximity to Westfield Chermside makes it a practical investment destination for buyers who are focused on yield and tenant quality rather than owner-occupier lifestyle. These buyers are analytical and efficient. They have run the numbers, understand what a Virginia property is likely to rent for, and move quickly when a property meets their criteria at an appropriate price.</p>

      <p>Airport and northern corridor workers represent a significant owner-occupier buyer group. Buyers who work at the Brisbane Airport precinct, in the Chermside health and commercial hub, or along the broader northern employment corridor often find that Virginia sits at a genuinely practical point relative to their daily commute. These buyers are not optimising for CBD proximity; they are optimising for northern corridor access, and Virginia delivers that efficiently. When they find a residential property that meets their requirements on a street that suits owner-occupier living, they compete with genuine motivation.</p>

      <p>First home buyers looking for an accessible northern Brisbane price point also participate in the Virginia market, particularly for units and townhouses in the suburb's more residential pockets. The proximity to Westfield Chermside and the Airport Link connection to the CBD make Virginia a practical choice for first buyers who prioritise northern Brisbane but cannot stretch to Aspley or Chermside prices.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Virginia</h2>
      <p>Street character is the single most important variable in Virginia's property market. The suburb's mixed industrial-residential character means that a property on a quiet, established residential street and a property with industrial or main-road exposure are priced very differently, even when other attributes are similar. Buyers who are considering Virginia for owner-occupier living are acutely aware of this distinction and will not pay residential prices for a location that does not feel like a residential address. If your property is in one of Virginia's genuine residential pockets, ensure your campaign communicates that clearly.</p>

      <p>Proximity to Virginia Golf Club is a meaningful amenity signal for owner-occupier buyers. The Golf Club provides green space and a community focal point that the suburb's commercial and industrial character would otherwise lack, and properties that are a short walk from the club benefit from that proximity in buyer assessments. This is particularly true for buyers who are choosing Virginia for quality-of-life reasons rather than purely investment ones.</p>

      <p>Airport Link access is a genuine selling point for buyers in the northern corridor. Commute time to the CBD from Virginia via Airport Link is competitive with many inner suburban options, and buyers who understand this can be persuaded to extend their search to Virginia when it offers better value than alternatives. Highlighting the suburb's transport connectivity clearly rather than assuming buyers will research it independently is a practical campaign decision.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Virginia home for sale</h2>
      <p>Virginia's investor buyer profile demands that a property presents as a clean, low-maintenance investment proposition. Internal presentation matters: a fresh coat of paint, clean carpets, and a functional kitchen and bathroom reassure investors that the property is tenant-ready. The investor buyer is not romanticised by styling or staging in the same way an owner-occupier is, but presentation quality does affect buyer confidence in the property's condition and the rental premium it will attract.</p>

      <p>For properties targeting owner-occupier buyers in the residential pockets, the preparation calculus shifts. These buyers are evaluating the property as a home, and the outdoor area, natural light, and street amenity become more important. A clear, clean, well-presented home on a genuine residential street should be styled to show its liveability, not just its investment metrics.</p>

      <p>A building and pest inspection completed before the campaign launch is worthwhile in Virginia's housing stock, which includes a range of older detached homes where condition findings are common. Completing the inspection before buyers arrive means you control the condition narrative rather than having buyers use their own mid-campaign findings to reduce your price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Virginia</h2>
      <p>Virginia's investor-weighted buyer pool is less seasonally sensitive than a purely residential suburb's market. Investors are active across the full calendar year and tend to be driven by their own portfolio timing rather than the seasonal rhythms that move family buyers. That said, the autumn campaign from late February through May and the spring campaign from September through November remain the periods of highest overall buyer activity in Brisbane, and listing in one of these windows gives you the broadest possible pool of active buyers including both investors and the owner-occupier segment.</p>

      <p>The northern corridor employment cycle can create pockets of demand at specific times of year. Buyers relocating for airport precinct or northern corridor roles tend to be active in late summer and early autumn as professional relocations take effect. A campaign launched in February or March sits well in front of this demand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Virginia</h2>
      <p>Well-priced Virginia properties, particularly those clearly in the residential pockets and targeted at the active investor buyer pool, typically sell within 28 to 45 days. The investor buyer moves efficiently when a property meets their yield and location criteria at a price that reflects current comparable sales. Overpricing relative to recent Virginia transactions and the Chermside and Aspley alternatives investors are running in parallel stalls campaigns; investors are analytical and patient, and they will wait for a correction rather than stretch past their yield targets. Correct pricing against current comparable sales is the essential precondition for a timely result in this market.</p>

